Databricks account setup	COE should own this because the Databricks account setup is not just an infrastructure task. It defines how workspaces, admins, users, groups, entitlements, and platform standards are managed going forward. Cloud Platform can help with AWS prerequisites, but COE needs to own the Databricks-side setup to make sure the platform is consistent and supportable.
Databricks audit logging and platform monitoring/alerting	COE should own this because COE understands what needs to be monitored inside Databricks — such as cluster events, job failures, workspace access, Unity Catalog permission changes, SQL warehouse activity, and admin actions. Cloud Platform can help send logs to enterprise monitoring tools, but COE should define the Databricks audit and alerting requirements.
Security and compliance baseline for Databricks	COE should own this because Databricks security includes more than AWS controls. It includes workspace access, Unity Catalog permissions, cluster policies, secrets, runtime controls, audit logging, service principals, and data access standards. Since COE is responsible for how Databricks is used by application teams, COE should define the Databricks security baseline.
Serverless egress controls — FQDN allowlists and S3 destination rules	COE should own the Databricks-side egress controls because these settings directly control what Databricks serverless compute can access. This is important for preventing unapproved external access and data movement. Cloud Platform can help where firewall, DNS, or networking is involved, but COE should own the Databricks policy and approved usage pattern.
Create Unity Catalog metastore and delegate metastore admin	COE should own this because Unity Catalog is the main governance layer inside Databricks. The metastore controls catalogs, schemas, tables, volumes, permissions, lineage, and workspace bindings. If this is not owned by COE, the data governance model can become inconsistent across workspaces and teams.
Workspace topology, environments, naming, and tagging standards	COE should own this because all Databricks workspaces need to follow a consistent pattern for dev, test, UAT, and prod. COE should define how workspaces are named, tagged, separated, and governed. This avoids every team creating their own structure and makes the platform easier to manage and audit.
Catalog creation per app team	COE should own catalog creation because catalogs are part of Unity Catalog governance. COE needs to make sure each app team gets the right catalog structure, naming standard, workspace binding, and permission model. App teams can own their data objects, but COE should control the catalog setup pattern.
Define CI/CD tooling and deployment model — Databricks Asset Bundles, Terraform, or both	COE should own this because Databricks deployments need a standard approach across teams. This includes notebooks, jobs, workflows, Databricks Asset Bundles, Databricks Terraform resources, service principals, and environment promotion. Cloud Platform can own AWS Terraform, but COE should own the Databricks deployment model.
Set up service principals for automated deployments per workspace	COE should own this because service principals are used for automated Databricks deployments and job execution. They affect production access, auditability, run-as identity, and least-privilege controls. COE needs to make sure these identities are created and used consistently across workspaces.
Define cluster policies and compute policies per workspace/environment	COE should own this because cluster policies are one of the main controls inside Databricks. They define approved runtimes, instance types, autoscaling limits, security mode, tags, libraries, and cost controls. Cloud Platform owns the underlying AWS infrastructure, but COE should own how Databricks compute is governed and used.
Create app team onboarding guide	COE should own this because app teams need clear instructions on how to use the Databricks platform correctly. The guide should explain access requests, workspace usage, Unity Catalog permissions, CI/CD standards, compute policies, support process, and onboarding steps. This helps all teams onboard in a consistent way.
Publish onboarding runbook to Confluence	COE should own the runbook because it becomes the source of truth for Databricks onboarding and operations. It should document the Databricks standards, support model, access process, deployment steps, validation checks, and escalation paths. Cloud Platform can contribute AWS-related sections, but COE should own the overall Databricks runbook.
Databricks support	COE should own Databricks support because most platform issues will be Databricks-specific — workspace access, cluster startup, job failures, Unity Catalog permissions, SQL warehouse issues, runtime problems, libraries, service principals, and audit checks. Cloud Platform should be engaged only when the issue is related to AWS networking, IAM, S3, KMS, or infrastructure.
Workspace smoke tests — connectivity, compute spin-up, S3 access, UC permissions	COE should own smoke testing because this confirms whether the workspace is actually ready for app teams to use. COE needs to validate login, group access, compute startup, cluster policy enforcement, Unity Catalog access, S3 access through external locations, job execution, and audit visibility. Cloud Platform can help validate the AWS/network side, but COE should own the end-to-end Databricks readiness check.



“The reason COE owns these items is because they are Databricks platform responsibilities, not just AWS infrastructure tasks. Cloud Platform should own the AWS foundation like VPC, subnets, IAM, S3, KMS, DNS, and networking. But COE needs to own the Databricks layer — Unity Catalog, compute policies, workspace standards, CI/CD model, service principals, audit controls, onboarding, support, and validation — because that is what ensures the platform is secure, consistent, governed, and usable for all app teams.”
